df_teams = pd.read_csv('data/Teams.csv')

# Step 2: Merge dataframes on WinningTeamId and TeamId
DFCombined = pd.merge(df_results, df_teams, left_on='Wteam', right_on='Team_Id', how='inner')

1. The relationship between the penguin's bill length and bill depth for each species. (5 marks)

In [ ]:
## TODO: Check your attributes, make a graph using Matplotlib or Seaborn to show the relationship needed
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the dataset
url = 'https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mwaskom/seaborn-data/master/penguins.csv'
penguins = sns.load_dataset('penguins')

# Create a scatter plot
sns.scatterplot(x='bill_length_mm', y='bill_depth_mm', hue='species', data=penguins)

# Set plot title and labels
plt.title('Relationship between Bill Length and Bill Depth for Each Penguin Species')
plt.xlabel('Bill Length (mm)')
plt.ylabel('Bill Depth (mm)')

# Show the plot
plt.show()

What do you observe from the graph? (2 marks)

*There are three distinct clusters on the plot graph, each corresponding to a different penguin species: Adelie, Chinstrap, and Gentoo. Penguins of different species tend to have varying combinations of bill length and bill depth. Adelie penguins generally have a wide range of bill lengths and depths.

Chinstrap penguins seem to have a relatively consistent bill length and depth.

Gentoo penguins exhibit a wide range of bill lengths but with a narrower range of bill depths.

Why did you choose this type of graph? (2 marks)

Your answer here:

  • The scatter plot is chosen for its ability to represent the Relationship between two continuous variables and to visually separate different categories (penguin species) based on color, aiding in the interpretation of patterns and trends. Three reasons for choosing this graph Relationship Visualization, Species Differentiation, Cluster Indentification.

2. Suitable graph of the mean BMI (BMI not body_mass weight_in_kg/height(m2)) of female and male penguins. (Assume the height is the flipper length) (5 marks)

In [ ]:
#Your answer here
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming you have a DataFrame named 'penguins_df'
# Replace 'penguins.csv' with your actual dataset
penguins_df = pd.read_csv('data/penguins.csv')

# Calculate BMI for each penguin
penguins_df['BMI'] = penguins_df['body_mass_g'] / ((penguins_df['flipper_length_mm'] / 1000) ** 2)

# Group by gender and calculate mean BMI
mean_bmi_by_gender = penguins_df.groupby('sex')['BMI'].mean().reset_index()

# Plotting the mean BMI for female and male penguins
sns.barplot(x='sex', y='BMI', data=mean_bmi_by_gender)
plt.title("Mean BMI of Female and Male Penguins")
plt.xlabel("Gender")
plt.ylabel("Mean BMI")
plt.show()

What do you observe from the graph? (2 marks)

Observations from the graph

  • Mean BMI Comparison

    Difference or Similarity

    Error Bars

    Visualizing Trends

Why did you choose this type of graph? (2 marks)

The chosen point plot with error bars is effective for comparing mean BMI between female and male penguins, providing a clear and concise representation of the data.

Reasons for choosing the graph:

Comparison of Categorical Data

Error Bars for Variability

Visual Clarity

Simple and Informative

Convince the museum board

The Firehouse Museum claims they ran an event in 2014 that brought an incredible number of visitors, and that they should get extra budget to run a similar event again. The other museums think these types of events aren't that important, and budgets should be split purely based on recent visitors on an average day.

To show the museum board how the event compared to regular traffic at each museum, create a suitable chart that shows how the number of visitors to each museum evolved over time. (4 marks)

In [ ]:
#Your solution here

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the museum visitors data 
file_path = "data/museum_visitors.csv"
museum_df = pd.read_csv(file_path)

# Check the structure of the dataset
print(museum_df.head())

# Convert the 'Date' column to datetime format
museum_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(museum_df['Date'])

# Create a line chart to show the evolution of visitors over time for each museum
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Iterate through each museum and plot the number of visitors over time
for museum in museum_df.columns[1:]:
    plt.plot(museum_df['Date'], museum_df[museum], label=museum)

# Highlight the year 2014 for emphasis on the event
plt.axvline(pd.to_datetime('2014-01-01'), color='red', linestyle='--', label='Event Year (2014)')

# Set plot title and labels
plt.title('Evolution of Museum Visitors Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of Visitors')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

# Load the data from the CSV file
gasprices_csv = pd.read_csv('c:/Users/Raman/Downloads/RamanA/gas_prices.csv')

# Melt the DataFrame to make it tidy
tidy_gasprices_data = gasprices_csv.melt(id_vars='Year', var_name='Country', value_name='Gas Price')

# Plotting the gas prices for each country over all years
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.lineplot(x='Year', y='Gas Price', hue='Country', data=tidy_gasprices_data)
plt.title('Gas Prices Over the Years for Each Country')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Gas Price')
plt.legend(title='Country', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.show()

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Assuming gasprices_csv is a DataFrame with columns: 'Year', 'Australia', 'Canada', ..., 'USA'

# Melt the DataFrame to make it tidy
tidy_gasprices_data = gasprices_csv.melt(id_vars='Year', var_name='Country', value_name='Gas Price')

# Plotting a box plot to show the distribution of gas prices for each country in a specific year
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
sns.boxplot(x='Country', y='Gas Price', data=tidy_gasprices_data)
plt.title('Distribution of Gas Prices Across Countries')
plt.xlabel('Country')
plt.ylabel('Gas Price')
plt.show()

Is there anything interesting observed from the plot/graph? (1 mark)

  • *Observations:

The box plot provides a clear overview of the central tendency and spread of gas prices for each country.

The boxes represent the interquartile range (IQR), showing where the majority of gas prices fall.

The whiskers extend to indicate the range of gas prices, and any points beyond the whiskers are considered outliers.

Outliers: Countries with gas prices that are significantly higher or lower than the majority. These outliers could be due to various factors such as economic conditions, geopolitical events, or other influences.

Variability: Compared the width and height of the boxes across countries. A wider box indicates higher variability in gas prices for that country.

Why did you choose this type of graph? (2 marks)

    • This type of graph is chosen for its ability to display the central tendency, spread, and identify outliers in the distribution of gas prices across multiple countries in a visually interpretable manner. It allows for a quick and effective comparison of the gas price distribution for each country.
